LEGIONELLOSIS - EUROPE (05): 2011-2015
**************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 07 July 2017
Source: Microservices [In Spanish, trans. Mod.JG, edited]
http://www.microservices.es/un-veinte-por-cien-de-los-casos-de-legionellosis-en-europa-estan-asociados-con-viajes


A study has been published in Eurosurveillance, which compiled all the data on legionnaires' disease in Europe for the period 2011 to 2015 [1]. This publication is from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control. The epidemiological surveillance of legionellosis in Europe is managed by the European Legionnaires' disease Surveillance Network (ELDSNET).

Between 2011 and 2015, 29 European countries reported 30 532 cases of legionnaires' disease (28 188 confirmed cases, and 2344 probable cases).

A total of 4 countries (Germany, France, Italy, and Spain) accounted for 70.3 percent of the total number of cases, but these countries represent half (50 percent) of the European population.

The [incidence] rate for legionellosis increased from 0.97 per 100 000 inhabitants in 2011 to 1.30 in 2015.

Up to 80 percent of cases occurred in persons more than 50-years-old, and the [case fatality] rate was 9.3 percent; the data has been stable for the last 5 years.
Only 0.5% percent of the cases (159) had occurred in persons less than 20-years-old.

In nearly 20 percent of the cases (19.9 percent, 5357), the infection was associated with travel and with staying outside home during the usual incubation period.

The cases associated with healthcare facilities were 1973, representing 7.3 percent of the total number.

Nearly 10 percent of the cases (9.9 percent) were associated with an outbreak or to a cluster, and the remaining 90.1 percent were isolated cases.

The causative microorganism was _Legionella pneumophila_ in 96.2 percent of the cases, and the serogroup 1 was the most frequently identified, accounting for 82.9 percent of all.

[1. Beaut√© J, on behalf of the European Legionnaires' Disease Surveillance Network. Legionnaires' disease in Europe, 2011 to 2015. Eurosurveillance 2017;22(27):pii=30566. DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.2807/1560-7917.ES.2017.22.27.30566. Available at http://eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=22829.]

