[The follow is the abstract extracted from reference 1 above:

Abstract
--------
"Under the coordination of the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC), the European Legionnaires' disease Surveillance Network (ELDSNet) conducts surveillance of Legionnaires' disease (LD) in Europe. Between 2011 and 2015, 29 countries reported 30 532 LD cases to ECDC (28 188 (92.3 percent) confirmed and 2344 (7.7 percent) probable). Four countries (France, Germany, Italy and Spain) accounted for 70.3 percent of all reported cases, although their combined populations represented only 49.9 percent of the study population. The age-standardized rate of all cases increased from 0.97 cases/100 000 population in 2011 to 1.30 cases/100 000 population in 2015, corresponding to an annual average increase of 0.09 cases/100 000 population (95 percent CI 0.02-0.14; 0.02). Demographics and infection setting remained unchanged with ca 70 percent of cases being community-acquired and 80 percent occurring in people aged 50 years and older. Clinical outcome was known for 23 164 cases, of whom 2161 (9.3 percent) died. The overall case fatality ratio decreased steadily from 10.5 percent in 2011 to 8.1 percent in 2015, probably reflecting improved reporting completeness. Five countries (Austria, Czech Republic, Germany, Italy, and Norway) had increasing age-standardised LD notification rates over the 2011-15 period, but there was no increase in notification rates in countries where the 2011 rate was below 0.5/100 000 population." - Mod.ML

